        <dictentrygrp id="YP0011147975280">
            <term>DEFENSE; DEFENCE; DEFENSE MECHANISM; DEFENCE MECHANISMS</term>
            <dictalso type="trans">
                <term lang="en">defence</term>
                <term lang="de">Abwehr</term>
                <term lang="fr">d&#233;fense</term>
                <term lang="es">defence</term>
                <term lang="it">difesa</term>
                <term lang="po">defesa</term>
            </dictalso>
            <dictentry>
                <term>Defence Mechanisms</term>
                <src>Laplanche, J. and Pontalis, J. B. (1973). The Language of
                    Psycho-Analysis.</src>
                <def type="def" name="Defence Mechanisms">
                    <p>= <i>D</i>.: Abwehrmechanismen.&#8211;<i>Es</i>.: mecanismos de
                            defensa.&#8211;<i>Fr</i>.: m&#233;canismes de
                            d&#233;fense.&#8211;<i>I</i>.: meccanismi di difesa.&#8211;<i>P</i>.:
                        mecanismos de defesa.</p>
                    <p>
                        <b>Different types of operations through which <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defence</impx> may be given specific expression. Which of these
                            mechanisms predominate in a given case depends upon the type of <impx
                                type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0018480381670" grpname="ILLNESS"
                                >illness</impx> under consideration, upon the developmental <impx
                                type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0001821354950"
                                grpname="STAGE; PHASE">stage</impx> reached, upon the extent to
                            which the defensive <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                                grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">conflict</impx> has been
                            worked out, and so on.</b>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <b>It is generally agreed that the ego puts the <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defence mechanisms</impx> to use, but the theoretical question of
                            whether their mobilisation always presupposes the <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0017512081750" grpname="EXISTENCE"
                                >existence</impx> of an organised ego capable of sustaining them is
                            an open one.</b>
                    </p>
                </def>
                <defrest>
                    <p>Freud\'s choice of the word &#8216;mechanism&#8217; is intended, from the
                        outset, to indicate the fact that psychical phenomena are so organised as to
                        permit of scientific observation and analysis; adequate confirmation of this
                        is provided by the mere title of Breuer and Freud\'s &#8216;Preliminary
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0000606445570"
                            grpname="COMMUNICATION">Communication</impx>&#8217; (<bx
                            r="IPL.094.0001A.B004">1893<i>a</i></bx>): &#8216;On the Psychical
                        Mechanism of Hysterical Phenomena&#8217;.</p>
                    <p>At a time when Freud was engaged in developing the concept of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>, making it the defining <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0017496848910"
                            grpname="PLEASURE; UNPLEASURE PRINCIPLE">principle</impx> of hysterical
                        phenomena (see &#8216;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defence</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690" grpname="Hysteria"
                            >Hysteria</impx>&#8217;), he was simultaneously seeking to specify other
                        psychoneurotic illnesses in terms of the mode of operation of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> peculiar to each: &#8216;&#8230; different <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0013496709810"
                            grpname="Neurosis; Neurotic">neurotic</impx> disturbances arise from the
                        different methods adopted by the &#8220;ego&#8221; in order to escape from
                        [its] incompatibility [with an idea]&#8217; <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B716"
                            >1</bx>.</p>
                    <p>Thus, in his &#8216;Further Remarks on the Neuro-Psychoses of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defence</impx>&#8217; (<bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B012">1896<i>b</i></bx>),
                        Freud distinguishes between the mechanisms of hysterical <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0019761794460" grpname="Conversion"
                            >conversion</impx>, obsessional <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0008010190570" grpname="SUBSTITUTION"
                            >substitution</impx> and paranoiac <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530" grpname="Projection"
                            >projection</impx>.</p>
                    <p>The term &#8216;mechanism&#8217; appears sporadically throughout Freud\'s
                        work. As for &#8216;mechanism of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>&#8217;, it is to be met with for example in the
                        metapsychological writings of 1915, and this in two rather different senses:
                        it is used either to denote the <i>whole</i> of that defensive process which
                        is characteristic of a given <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0013496709810" grpname="Neurosis; Neurotic"
                            >neurosis</impx>
                        <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B717">2</bx>, or else to mean the defensive employment
                        of a <i>particular</i> &#8216;instinctual vicissitude&#8217; (<impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YN0005156508250"
                            grpname="Turning Round upon the Subject\'s Own Self">turning round upon
                            the subject\'s own self</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0008172626820" grpname="Reversal into the Opposite"
                            >reversal into the opposite</impx>) <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B718"
                        >3</bx>.</p>
                    <p>In <i>Inhibitions, Symptoms and Anxiety</i> (<bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B089"
                                >1926<i>d</i></bx>), Freud justifies what he calls his
                        &#8216;re-introduction of the old concept of <i>defence&#8217;</i>
                        <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B719">4<i>a</i></bx> on the grounds that it is
                        necessary to have an inclusive category under which other &#8216;methods of
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>&#8217;, aside from <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>, may be subsumed. He stresses the possibility of
                        establishing &#8216;an intimate connection between special forms of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> and particular illnesses&#8217;, and concludes by
                        putting forward the hypothesis that &#8216;before its sharp cleavage into an
                        ego and an id, and before the formation of a <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0003128406840" grpname="SUPEREGO; Super-Ego"
                            >super-ego</impx>, the mental apparatus makes use of different methods
                        of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> from those which it employs after it has reached these
                        stages of organization&#8217; <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B719">4<i>b</i></bx>.</p>
                    <p>Although Freud appears, in this passage, to underestimate the extent to which
                        such ideas have been constantly discernible in his work up to this point,
                        there is no <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008498107090"
                            grpname="DOUBT">doubt</impx> that from 1926 onwards the study of the
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence mechanisms</impx> is to</p>
                    <p2>become a major theme of psycho-analytic research. This <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240" grpname="DEVELOPMENT"
                            >development</impx> was spearheaded by <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0016730370470" grpname="Freud, Anna; Anna Freud"
                            >Anna Freud</impx>\'s book devoted to the topic, in which, basing
                        herself on concrete examples, she attempts to describe the variety,
                        complexity and compass of the mechanisms of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>. In particular, she shows how defensive aims may make
                        use of the most varied activities (<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0010700504210" grpname="Fantasy; Phantasy"
                            >phantasy</impx>, intellectual activity) and how <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> can be directed not only against instinctual claims but
                        also against everything which is liable to give rise to the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240" grpname="DEVELOPMENT"
                            >development</impx> of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx>:
                        emotions, situations, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0003128406840"
                            grpname="SUPEREGO; Super-Ego">super-ego</impx> demands, etc. It may be
                        noted that <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0016730370470"
                            grpname="Freud, Anna; Anna Freud">Anna Freud</impx> does not claim that
                        her approach is either exhaustive or systematic&#8211;a reservation which
                        applies especially to her incidental enumeration of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence mechanisms</impx>. Her list includes: <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0009718260130" grpname="Regression"
                            >regression</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0017025529300" grpname="REACTION FORMATION"
                            >reaction-formation</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770" grpname="Isolation"
                        >isolation</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950"
                            grpname="Undoing">undoing</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530" grpname="Projection"
                            >projection</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0005203457490" grpname="Introject; Introjection"
                            >introjection</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0001932408610" grpname="TURNING AGAINST THE SELF"
                            >turning against the self</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0008172626820" grpname="Reversal into the Opposite"
                            >reversal into the opposite</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960" grpname="Sublimation"
                            >sublimation</impx>*.</p2>
                    <p>Many other defensive procedures have been described. <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0016730370470" grpname="Freud, Anna; Anna Freud"
                            >Anna Freud</impx> herself further brings under this heading the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0013831327350"
                            grpname="SCHIZOID PERSONALITY; PROCESSES">processes</impx> of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015547544960"
                            grpname="Denial; Disavowal">denial</impx> in <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0010700504210" grpname="Fantasy; Phantasy"
                            >phantasy</impx>, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0003353926610"
                            grpname="IDEALIZATION; Idealisation">idealisation</impx>*, <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0014376592790"
                            grpname="Identification with the Aggressor">identification with the
                            aggressor</impx>*, etc. <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001k.YN0012380833000"
                            grpname="KLEIN, MELANIE; MELANIE KLEIN">Melanie Klein</impx> describes
                        what she considers to be very primitive defences: <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0019876869000" grpname="Splitting of the Object"
                            >splitting of the object</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0014993008580" grpname="Projective Identification"
                            >projective identification</impx>*, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015547544960" grpname="Denial; Disavowal"
                            >denial</impx> of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0003664264220"
                            grpname="Psychic reality">psychic reality</impx>, omnipotent control
                        over objects, etc.</p>
                    <p>Inevitably, the blanket use of the concept of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> mechanism raises a number of problems. When operations
                        as diverse as, say, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YP0018435949270"
                            grpname="RATIONALIZATION">rationalisation</impx>*, which brings <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0011849881830" grpname="Complex"
                            >complex</impx> intellectual mechanisms into play, and <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0001932408610"
                            grpname="TURNING AGAINST THE SELF">turning against the self</impx>,
                        which is a &#8216;vicissitude&#8217; of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0014567859780"
                            grpname="INSTINCTUAL DRIVE; Instinctual Aim; Instinctual Object"
                            >instinctual aim</impx>, are attributed to a single function, and when
                        the same term &#8216;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>&#8217; connotes such a truly compulsive operation as
                            &#8216;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950"
                            grpname="Undoing">undoing</impx> what has been done&#8217; as well as
                        the search for a form of &#8216;working-off&#8217; after the fashion of
                        certain kinds of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960"
                            grpname="Sublimation">sublimation</impx> (see &#8216;Working-Off
                        Mechanisms&#8217;), then it may well be asked whether the concept in
                        question is a really operational one.</p>
                    <p>Many authors, while speaking of &#8216;ego <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence-mechanisms</impx>&#8217;, do not hesitate to distinguish
                        between different sub-categories: &#8216;Methods such as that of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950" grpname="Undoing"
                            >undoing</impx> and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770" grpname="Isolation">isolation</impx>
                        stand side by side with genuine instinctual <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0013831327350"
                            grpname="SCHIZOID PERSONALITY; PROCESSES">processes</impx>, such as
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0009718260130"
                            grpname="Regression">regression</impx>, reversal and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0001932408610" grpname="TURNING AGAINST THE SELF"
                            >turning against the self</impx>&#8217; <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B720"
                                >5<i>a</i></bx>. At this point, however, it becomes necessary to
                        show how the same process can function on different levels; for instance,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0005203457490"
                            grpname="Introject; Introjection">introjection</impx>, which is first
                        and foremost a mode of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx>\'s <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0013074626040" grpname="RELATION"
                            >relation</impx> to its <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070" grpname="Object">object</impx>,
                        having its somatic prototype in the act of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0009418688200" grpname="Incorporation"
                            >incorporation</impx>, can be made use of <i>secondarily</i> by the ego
                        for the purposes of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> (particularly manic <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>).</p>
                    <p>Another fundamental theoretical distinction ought not to be
                        overlooked&#8211;namely, the distinction which marks off <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx> from all other defensive <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0013831327350"
                            grpname="SCHIZOID PERSONALITY; PROCESSES">processes</impx>. Freud had no
                        qualms about recalling this specificity even after having said that <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx> was merely a special case of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>
                        <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B721">6</bx>. This uniqueness of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx> is not due so much to the fact&#8211;invoked by <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0016730370470"
                            grpname="Freud, Anna; Anna Freud">Anna Freud</impx>&#8211;that it may be
                        defined, in essence, as a permanent <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0021094072950"
                            grpname="ANTICATHEXIS; COUNTERCATHEXIS">anticathexis</impx>*, and that
                        it is at once &#8216;the most efficacious and the most dangerous&#8217; of
                        the mechanisms of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>: its special function derives rather from its role in
                        the constitution of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YN0015567349630"
                            grpname="The unconscious">the unconscious</impx> as such (see
                            &#8216;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >Repression</impx>&#8217;).</p>
                    <p>Lastly, there is a danger that by basing the theory on the idea of the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx></p>
                    <p2><i>of the ego</i> one may easily be brought to set this against a supposedly
                        pure instinctual <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0007446770570"
                            grpname="DEMAND">demand</impx> which, by definition, is devoid of any
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015623364070"
                            grpname="DIALECTIC">dialectic</impx> of its own: &#8216;Were it not for
                        the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0011199470610"
                            grpname="INTERVENTION">intervention</impx> of the ego, or of those
                        external forces which the ego represents, every <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx> would know only
                        one fate&#8211;that of gratification&#8217; <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B720"
                                >5<i>b</i></bx>.</p2>
                    <p>The upshot of this line of reasoning is that the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx> comes to be seen
                        as a completely positive force, bearing the traces of no prohibition. But do
                        not the <i>mechanisms</i> of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0019823102420"
                            grpname="Primary Process; Secondary Process">primary process</impx>
                            itself&#8211;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0002322384630"
                            grpname="Displacement">displacement</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0012338717130" grpname="Condensation"
                            >condensation</impx>, etc.&#8211;with their implication that the
                        interplay of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instincts</impx> is structured,
                        stand in contradiction to this approach?</p>
