            <dictentry>
                <term>Defence</term>
                <src>Laplanche, J. and Pontalis, J. B. (1973). The Language of
                    Psycho-Analysis.</src>
                <def type="def" name="Defence">
                    <p>= <i>D</i>.: Abwehr.&#8211;<i>Es</i>.: defensa.&#8211;<i>Fr</i>.:
                            d&#233;fense.&#8211;<i>I</i>.: difesa.&#8211;<i>P</i>.: defesa.</p>
                    <p>
                        <b>Group of operations</b>
                        <bi>aimed at</bi>
                        <b>the reduction and elimination of any change liable to threaten the
                            integrity and stability of the bio-psychological individual. Inasmuch as
                            the ego is constituted as an <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0012579328430" grpname="Agency">agency</impx>
                            which embodies this stability and strives</b>
                    </p>
                    <p2>
                        <b>to maintain it, it may be considered as both the</b>
                        <bi>stake</bi>
                        <b>and the</b>
                        <bi>agent</bi>
                        <b>of these operations.</b>
                    </p2>
                    <p>
                        <b>Generally speaking, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defence</impx> is</b>
                        <bi>directed towards</bi>
                        <b>internal <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0012482820020"
                                grpname="EXCITATION">excitation</impx> (<impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                                grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx>); in
                            practice, its <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0005417015680"
                                grpname="ACTION">action</impx> is extended to whatever
                            representations* (memories, phantasies) this <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0012482820020" grpname="EXCITATION"
                                >excitation</impx> is bound to; and to any situation that is
                            unpleasurable for the ego as a result of its incompatibility with the
                            individual\'s equilibrium and, to that extent, liable to spark off the
                                <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0012482820020"
                                grpname="EXCITATION">excitation</impx>. Unpleasurable <impx
                                type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                                grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affects</impx>*, which serve as</b>
                        <bi>motives</bi>
                        <b>or</b>
                        <bi>signals</bi>
                        <b>for <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defence</impx>, may also become its <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070" grpname="Object"
                            >object</impx>.</b>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <b>The defensive process is expressed concretely in</b>
                        <bi>mechanisms</bi>
                        <b> of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defence</impx> which are more or less integrated into the ego.</b>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <b><impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >Defence</impx> is marked and infiltrated by its ultimate <impx
                                type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070" grpname="Object"
                                >object</impx>&#8211;<impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                                grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx>&#8211;and
                            consequently it often takes on a compulsive aspect, and works at least
                            in part in an <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0013420666620"
                                grpname="Unconscious">unconscious</impx> way.</b>
                    </p>
                </def>
                <defrest>
                    <p>It was by bringing the notion of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> to the force in dealing with <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690" grpname="Hysteria"
                        >hysteria</impx>&#8211;and, soon afterwards, with the other
                        psychoneuroses*&#8211;that Freud developed his own <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0014788201080" grpname="PRECONCEPTION; CONCEPTION"
                            >conception</impx> of mental life in contrast to the views of his
                        contemporaries (see &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defence</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690" grpname="Hysteria"
                            >Hysteria</impx>&#8217;). The <i>Studies on Hysteria</i> (<bx
                            r="IPL.094.0001A.B010">1895<i>d</i></bx>) demonstrate all the complexity
                        of the relations between <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> and the ego which is made responsible for it. The ego in
                        question is that area of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0021254895470"
                            grpname="PERSONALITY; Personality Disorder"
                        >personality</impx>&#8211;that &#8216;space&#8217;&#8211;which seeks freedom
                        from all forms of disturbance&#8211;from conflicts between contradictory
                        wishes for instance. It is further a &#8216;group of ideas&#8217; at
                        variance with an idea* deemed &#8216;incompatible&#8217; with itself; the
                        sign of this incompatibility is an unpleasurable <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affect</impx>. Lastly, it is the agent of the defensive operation (see
                        &#8216;Ego&#8217;). In the works in which he evolves the concept of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> neuro-<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0013026678540" grpname="Psychosis"
                        >psychosis</impx>*, Freud invariably places the emphasis on the notion of
                        the incompatibility of an idea with the ego; the different forms of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> are seen as corresponding to the different <i>ways</i>
                        in which this idea is dealt with, particularly in so far as these procedures
                        make use of the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0017378833180"
                            grpname="SEPARATION">separation</impx> of the idea from the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affect</impx> which was originally bound to
                        it. At the same time, it will be recalled that Freud very soon opposed the
                        neuro-psychoses of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> to the actual neuroses*, these <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YN0015659043440" grpname="BEING">being</impx> a group
                        of neuroses where an intolerable increase in internal tension, due to an
                        undischarged sexual <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0012482820020"
                            grpname="EXCITATION">excitation</impx>, finds an outlet in a variety of
                        somatic <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0011868560200"
                            grpname="Symptom; Symptom Formation; Symptomatic Act">symptoms</impx>.
                        It is significant that Freud refuses to speak of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> in the case of the actual neuroses, despite the fact
                        that they do involve a form of self-protection on the part of the organism
                        and the attempt to restore a certain equilibrium. From the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0001417964900" grpname="MOMENT"
                            >moment</impx> of its discovery, then, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> is implicitly distinguished from those measures which an
                        organism takes to reduce any increase in tension whatsoever.</p>
                    <p>At the same time as trying to specify the different modalities of the
                        defensive process according to the various mental illnesses, and while his
                        clinical experience was enabling him&#8211;in the <i>Studies on
                        Hysteria</i>&#8211;to give a more accurate account of the steps in this
                        process (the re-emergence of the unpleasurable <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx> which have served as motives for <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>, the layering of resistances, the stratification of the
                        pathogenic <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YN0018787855710"
                            grpname="Material">material</impx>, etc.), Freud was also attempting to
                        construct a metapsychological model of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>. This theory refers from the outset to a distinction
                        that Freud was always to maintain subsequently: that</p>
                    <p2>between <i>external</i> excitations on the one hand, from which <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YP0011373079650" grpname="FIGHT; FLIGHT"
                            >flight</impx> is possible or against which a damming mechanism is set
                        up for the purpose of filtering them (see &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0017849911590" grpname="Protective Shield"
                            >Protective Shield</impx>&#8217;) and, on the other hand,
                            <i>internal</i> excitations which it is impossible to evade. It is in
                        answer to this <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0013535936150"
                            grpname="AGGRESSION; AGRESSIVENESS">aggression</impx> from the
                        inside&#8211;in other words, against <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx>&#8211;that the
                        different defensive procedures are instigated. The &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000016909940"
                            grpname="PROJECT FOR A SCIENTIFIC PSYCHOLOGY">Project for a Scientific
                            Psychology</impx>&#8217; (<bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B104">1950<i>a</i></bx>
                        [1895]) tackles the problem of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> in two ways:</p2>
                    <p>a. Freud seeks the origin of what he calls &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760" grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain"
                            >primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>&#8217; in an &#8216;experience of pain&#8217;, just as
                        he had found the model of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0004718997320" grpname="DESIRE">desire</impx> and
                        its <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0016814763690"
                            grpname="INHIBITION">inhibition</impx> by the ego in an &#8216;<impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0017014921470"
                            grpname="Experience of Satisfaction">experience of
                        satisfaction</impx>&#8217;*. This <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0014788201080" grpname="PRECONCEPTION; CONCEPTION"
                            >conception</impx>, however, is not expounded with the same clarity, in
                        the &#8216;Project&#8217; itself, as that of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0017014921470" grpname="Experience of Satisfaction"
                            >experience of satisfaction</impx> (&#945;).</p>
                    <p>b. Freud attempts to differentiate a pathological form of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> from a normal form. The latter occurs in the case of the
                        revival of a distressing experience; in normal <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>, the ego must have been able to begin inhibiting the
                        unpleasure on the occasion of the initial experience by means of
                        &#8216;side-cathexes&#8217;: &#8216;If the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0005377732370" grpname="Cathexis">cathexis</impx> of
                        the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530" grpname="MEMORY"
                            >memory</impx> is repeated, the unpleasure is repeated too, but the
                        ego-facilitations are there already as well; experience shows that the
                        release [of unpleasure] is less the second time, until, after further <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YP0012477444570" grpname="REPETITION"
                            >repetition</impx>, it shrivels up to the intensity of a signal
                        acceptable to the ego&#8217; <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B712">1<i>a</i></bx>.</p>
                    <p>This kind of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> enables the ego to avoid the danger of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YN0015659043440" grpname="BEING"
                            >being</impx> over-whelmed and infiltrated by the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0019823102420"
                            grpname="Primary Process; Secondary Process">primary process</impx>*; in
                        pathological <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>, on the other hand, this is precisely what does happen.
                        As we know, Freud considers that this latter operation only comes into play
                        as a consequence of a sexual scene which, at the time, did not give rise to
                        normal <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> but whose <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530" grpname="MEMORY">memory</impx>, once
                        reactivated, triggers off a rise in <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0012482820020" grpname="EXCITATION"
                            >excitation</impx> from the inside. &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0019477127470" grpname="ATTENTION">Attention</impx>
                        is [normally] adjusted towards perceptions, which are what ordinarily give
                        occasion for a release of unpleasure. Here [however, what has appeared] is
                        no <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0010827467910"
                            grpname="PERCEPTION">perception</impx> but a <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530" grpname="MEMORY">memory</impx>, which
                        unexpectedly releases unpleasure, and the ego only discovers this too
                        late&#8217; <bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B712">1<i>b</i></bx>. Which explains
                        &#8216;the fact that in the case of an <i>ego-process</i> consequences
                        follow to which we are accustomed only with <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760" grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain"
                            >primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0013831327350"
                            grpname="SCHIZOID PERSONALITY; PROCESSES">processes</impx>&#8217; <bx
                            r="IPL.094.0001A.B712">1<i>c</i></bx>.</p>
                    <p>Pathological <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> is thus conditional upon the setting in motion of an
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0012482820020"
                            grpname="EXCITATION">excitation</impx> of internal origin which brings
                        about unpleasure, and against which no defensive procedure has been learnt.
                        Its coming into play is not therefore motivated by the intensity of the
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affect</impx>
                        <i>per se</i>, but rather by quite specific conditions which are to be found
                        neither in the case of a distressing <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0010827467910" grpname="PERCEPTION"
                            >perception</impx>, nor even on the occasion of the recollection of such
                        a <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0010827467910" grpname="PERCEPTION"
                            >perception</impx>. For Freud, these conditions are only fulfilled in
                        the sexual realm (see &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008891296900"
                            grpname="Deferred Action; Deferred; DEFERRED ACTION; NACHTRAEGLICHKEIT"
                            >Deferred Action</impx>&#8217;, &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0003023539990" grpname="SEDUCTION"
                        >Seduction</impx>&#8217;).</p>
                    <p>However great the differences may be between the various modalities of the
                        defensive process in <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690"
                            grpname="Hysteria">hysteria</impx>, obsessional <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0013496709810" grpname="Neurosis; Neurotic"
                            >neurosis</impx>, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0017412347390"
                            grpname="PARANOIA; Paranoid Character; Paranoid Schizophrenia"
                            >paranoia</impx>, etc. (see &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defence Mechanisms</impx>&#8217;), the two poles of the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                            grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">conflict</impx> are invariably
                        the ego and the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx>: it is against an
                        internal threat that the ego seeks to defend itself. This <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0014788201080" grpname="PRECONCEPTION; CONCEPTION"
                            >conception</impx>, though validated constantly by clinical experience,
                        poses a theoretical problem which was never far from Freud\'s <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0019477127470" grpname="ATTENTION"
                            >attention</impx>: how does it</p>
                    <p2>come about that instinctual <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0019870290110" grpname="Discharge">discharge</impx>,
                        which is given over by definition to the attainment of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0017496848910"
                            grpname="PLEASURE; UNPLEASURE PRINCIPLE">pleasure</impx>, can be
                        perceived as unpleasure or as the threat of unpleasure to the point of
                        occasioning a defensive operation? It is true that the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0015613280530" grpname="Topography; Topographical"
                            >topographical</impx> diversification of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0011513343060" grpname="Psychical Apparatus"
                            >psychical apparatus</impx> clears the way for the thesis that what is
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0017496848910"
                            grpname="PLEASURE; UNPLEASURE PRINCIPLE">pleasure</impx> for one system
                        is unpleasure for another (i.e. the ego), but this distribution of roles
                        still leaves one question unanswered: what exactly leads certain instinctual
                        demands into opposition with the ego? Freud rejects a theoretical solution
                        along the lines that <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> arises &#8216;&#8230; in cases where the tension
                        produced by lack of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0007535286680"
                            grpname="SATISFACTION">satisfaction</impx> of an <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinctual impulse</impx> is
                        raised to an <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0009182452750"
                            grpname="UNBEARABLE">unbearable</impx> degree&#8217; <bx
                            r="IPL.094.0001A.B713">2</bx>. Unsatisfied hunger, for example, is not
                        repressed; whatever the &#8216;methods of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>&#8217; may be which are open to the organism for dealing
                        with a threat of this type, they certainly have nothing to do with <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> as it is known to <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0004507089640"
                            grpname="Psycho-Analysis; PSYCHOANALYSIS">psycho-analysis</impx>. And
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> cannot be adequately accounted for by <i>homoeostasis of
                            the organism</i>.</p2>
                    <p>So what is the ultimate basis of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> of the ego? Why does the ego experience a certain <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinctual impulse</impx> an
                        unpleasure? The question is fundamental to <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0004507089640"
                            grpname="Psycho-Analysis; PSYCHOANALYSIS">psycho-analysis</impx>, and
                        there are a variety of answers to it which are not necessarily mutually
                        exclusive. An initial distinction is often made as regards the fundamental
                        source of the danger which is inseparable from instinctual <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0007535286680" grpname="SATISFACTION"
                            >satisfaction</impx>: the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx> itself may be
                        deemed dangerous to the ego, and seen purely as an attack upon it from the
                        inside. Alternatively, all danger can be attributed, in the last reckoning,
                        to the individual\'s relations with the outside world: in this sense, the
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx> is only dangerous
                        because of the real harm which its <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0007535286680" grpname="SATISFACTION"
                            >satisfaction</impx> might bring in its wake. It is the latter option,
                        for example, which informs the thesis adopted by Freud in <i>Inhibitions,
                            Symptoms and Anxiety</i> (<bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B089">1926<i>d</i></bx>)
                        and, in particular, his new <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0003576847720" grpname="Interpretation"
                            >interpretation</impx> of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0011783783650" grpname="Phobia; Phobic Character"
                            >phobia</impx>; consequently, he promotes &#8216;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0006121425000"
                            grpname="ANXIETY, REALISTIC; REALISTIC ANXIETY">realistic
                        anxiety</impx>&#8217;* (<i>Realangst</i>) to a special status
                        and&#8211;carrying this tendency to the extreme&#8211;he treats <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0013496709810"
                            grpname="Neurosis; Neurotic">neurotic</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY"
                            >anxiety</impx>, or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx> in
                        the face of the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx>, as purely
                        derivative.</p>
                    <p>If the problem is approached from the standpoint of the way the ego is
                        conceived of, the solution will naturally vary according to whether the
                        stress is laid upon its function as the agent of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0014605906430" grpname="REALITY">reality</impx> and
                        the representative of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0014611118010" grpname="Reality Principle">reality
                            principle</impx>; or whether the main emphasis is placed instead on its
                            &#8216;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0011909677230"
                            grpname="COMPULSIONS">compulsion</impx> to synthesis&#8217;; or, again,
                        whether the ego is seen above all as a <i>gestalt</i>&#8211;a sort of
                        intrasubjective replica of the organism&#8211;governed, like the organism,
                        by a <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0017496848910"
                            grpname="PLEASURE; UNPLEASURE PRINCIPLE">principle</impx> of
                        homoeostasis. Lastly, from the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008220149200" grpname="Dynamic">dynamic</impx>
                        point of view, it is tempting to account for the difficulty raised by
                        unpleasure of instinctual origin by positing an antagonism not just between
                        the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instincts</impx> and the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0012579328430" grpname="Agency"
                            >agency</impx> of the ego but also between two kinds of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx> with differing
                        aims. Freud embarked upon just such a course in the years 1910-15, when he
                        set up an opposition between the sexual <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instincts</impx> and the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0004269630290"
                            grpname="Instincts of Self-Preservation">instincts of
                            self-preservation</impx> or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0007945313930" grpname="EGO INSTINCT; EGO DRIVES"
                            >ego-instincts</impx>. In his final theory, of course, this instinctual
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0016564103160"
                            grpname="Pair of Opposites">pair of opposites</impx> was to be replaced
                        by the antithesis between the life and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0020577893270" grpname="DEATH INSTINCT; DEATH DRIVE"
                            >death instincts</impx>&#8211;an opposition which no longer coincided
                        directly with the disposition of forces in the dynamics of the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                            grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">conflict</impx>*.</p>
                    <p>The term &#8216;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>&#8217; itself, especially when used in its absolute
                        sense, is full of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0006781673580"
                            grpname="AMBIGUITY">ambiguity</impx> and necessitates the introduction
                        of notional distinctions. It connotes both the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0005417015680" grpname="ACTION">action</impx> of
                            <i>defending</i>&#8211;in the sense of fighting to protect
                        something&#8211;and that of <i>defending oneself</i>. It might be of use
                        therefore to distinguish between different parameters of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>, even if these coincide with one another to some extent,
                        viz. <i>the stake of defence:</i> the &#8216;psychical space&#8217; which is
                        threatened; <i>the agent of defence:</i> whatever supports the defensive
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0005417015680" grpname="ACTION"
                            >action</impx>; <i>the aims of defence:</i> an example would be the
                        tendency to maintain and re-establish the integrity and the constancy of the
                        ego, and to avoid all perturbing factors liable to be transposed into
                        subjective unpleasure; <i>the motives of defence:</i> whatever heralds the
                        danger and sets the defensive process in motion (<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx> reduced to the function of signals, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx> as
                        signal*); and <i>the mechanisms of defence</i>.</p>
                    <p>A final point: the distinction between <i>defence</i>, in the virtually
                        strategic sense that it has acquired in <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0004507089640"
                            grpname="Psycho-Analysis; PSYCHOANALYSIS">psycho-analysis</impx>, and
                            <i>prohibition</i>, particularly as it is understood in the context of
                        the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0001894379240"
                            grpname="Oedipus Complex">Oedipus complex</impx>, underlines the
                        discrepancy which exists between the two levels of the structuring of the
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0011513343060"
                            grpname="Psychical Apparatus">psychical apparatus</impx> and the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0021397840800"
                            grpname="STRUCTURE, PSYCHIC; PSYCHIC STRUCTURE">structure</impx> of the
                        most fundamental wishes and phantasies; the question of the articulation of
                        these two levels in the theory and practice of the psychoanalytic cure
                        remains an open one.</p>
                    <quote>
                        <p>(&#945;) The thesis of an &#8216;experience of pain&#8217; taken to be
                            the diametrical opposite of the <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0017014921470"
                                grpname="Experience of Satisfaction">experience of
                                satisfaction</impx> is paradoxical from the outset, for why would
                            the neuronal apparatus repeat a pain&#8211;which is defined by an
                            increased charge&#8211;to the point of hallucinating it, when the
                            function of this apparatus is, precisely, the avoidance of any rise in
                            tension? This <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0007621182360"
                                grpname="PARADOX">paradox</impx> can be explained if one takes into
                            consideration the many passages in Freud\'s work in which he tackles the
                                <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YP0010725807690"
                                grpname="Economic">economic</impx> problem of pain. Any such
                            examination, in our opinion, reveals that physical pain, as a breach of
                            the confines of the body, ought rather to be taken as a model of that
                            internal <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0013535936150"
                                grpname="AGGRESSION; AGRESSIVENESS">aggression</impx> which the
                                <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                                grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx> constitutes
                            for the ego. The &#8216;experience of pain&#8217; should therefore be
                            understood not as an hallucinatory <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YP0012477444570" grpname="REPETITION"
                                >repetition</impx> of an actually experienced pain but rather as the
                            emergence, with the revival of an experience which may not have been
                            painful in itself, of that &#8216;pain&#8217; which <impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx>
                            consists of from the ego\'s point of view.</p>
                    </quote>
                    <p><list type="NNB"><li><be id="IPL.094.0001A.B712" label="1">Freud, S.: a)
                                        <i>Anf</i>., 438; <binc class="na"><bst>S.E.</bst>,
                                        <v>I</v>, <pp>359</pp>.</binc> b) <i>Anf</i>., 438; S.E., I,
                                    358, c) <i>Anf</i>., 432; <binc class="na"><bst>S.E.</bst>,
                                            <v>I</v>, <pp>353</pp>.</binc></be></li><li><be
                                    id="IPL.094.0001A.B713" label="2">Freud, S.
                                    &#8216;Repression&#8217; (<bx r="IPL.094.0001A.B056"
                                            >1915<i>d</i></bx>), <binc class="na"><bst>G.W.</bst>,
                                            <v>X</v>, <pp>249</pp>;</binc>
                                    <binc class="na"><bst>S.E.</bst>, <v>XIV</v>,
                                        <pp>147</pp>.</binc></be></li></list>\n</p>
                </defrest>
            </dictentry>
            <dictentry>
                <term>DEFENCE (FREUD)</term>
                <src>Skelton, R. (Ed.). (2006). The Edinburgh International Encyclopaedia of
                    Psychoanalysis.</src>
                <def>
                    <p>As a general concept, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> designates a variety of operations initiated by the ego
                        that share the aim of protecting the integrity of the individual. These
                        operations are known as mechanisms of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>.</p>
                </def>
                <defrest>
                    <p>In his early work, Freud conceives <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760" grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain"
                            >primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> as a byproduct of the experience of pain. This mechanism
                        is generated by the *ego in order to prevent the activation of a <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530" grpname="MEMORY"
                            >memory</impx> of a painful experience that would result in the release
                        of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affect</impx>. <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760" grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain"
                            >Primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> is a normal psychic process that prevents the occurrence
                        of a *<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0019823102420"
                            grpname="Primary Process; Secondary Process">primary process</impx>.
                        Unlike innate biological reflex <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0005417015680" grpname="ACTION">action</impx>, <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760"
                            grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain">primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> is the result of learning through experience.</p>
                    <p>Freud postulated in 1894 that some psychoneuroses were the product of
                        pathological <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx>. The compulsive and hyperintensive nature of the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0011868560200"
                            grpname="Symptom; Symptom Formation; Symptomatic Act">symptoms</impx> of
                        these neuroses was attributed to a process aimed at impeding the activation
                        of a painful <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530"
                            grpname="MEMORY">memory</impx>.</p>
                    <p>*<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >Repression</impx> was the first form of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001g.YP0006494278780"
                            grpname="GAIN; PRIMARYGain; Secondary">secondary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> postulated by Freud. This form of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> acts by severing the link between *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affect</impx> and *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0011615574840"
                            grpname="Symbolism; Symbolization; Representation; Symbolic Representation"
                            >representation</impx>, thus divesting the conflicting <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0011615574840"
                            grpname="Symbolism; Symbolization; Representation; Symbolic Representation"
                            >representation</impx> of its cathexes and making it unavailable to
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0005451837790"
                            grpname="CONSCIOUS">conscious</impx> consideration.</p>
                    <p>Although initiated by the ego, pathological <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> has all the characteristics of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760" grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain"
                            >primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0013831327350"
                            grpname="SCHIZOID PERSONALITY; PROCESSES">processes</impx>.</p>
                    <p>E. K.</p>
                </defrest>
                <bib alpha="true">
                    <be id="ZBK.060.0103A.B011" rx="IJP.044.0378" class="oos"><a><l>Fairbairn</l>,
