            <dictentry>
                <term>DEFENCE (EGO PSYCHOLOGY)</term>
                <src>Skelton, R. (Ed.). (2006). The Edinburgh International Encyclopaedia of
                    Psychoanalysis.</src>
                <dictalso>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0018611654130"
                        grpname="COMPROMISE FORMATION">compromise formation</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                        grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">conflict/intrapsychic
                        conflict</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                        grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms">defence
                        analysis</impx>
                </dictalso>
                <def>
                    <p>Defences are <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0013420666620"
                            grpname="Unconscious">unconscious</impx> psychological devices employed
                        by the patient when jeopardised by the emergence into <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004696678820" grpname="Consciousness"
                            >consciousness</impx> of repressed <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005442939990" grpname="DRIVE">drive</impx>
                        derivatives (fantasies, wishes, ideas, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx>), repressed memories and their associated <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affects</impx>, or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0000721059170" grpname="Confrontation"
                            >confrontation</impx> with intolerable aspects of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0014605906430" grpname="REALITY">reality</impx>.
                        They protect the ego from <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YN0015659043440" grpname="BEING">being</impx>
                        overwhelmed and traumatised by intolerably intense <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx>; pressing drives; <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0003128406840" grpname="SUPEREGO; Super-Ego"
                            >super-ego</impx> demands; <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0009182452750" grpname="UNBEARABLE"
                            >unbearable</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0014605906430" grpname="REALITY"
                            >reality</impx>; or psychic *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                            grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">conflict</impx>. <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005442939990" grpname="DRIVE"
                            >Drive</impx> derivatives, memories, or realities that have been
                        repressed but threaten to become <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0005451837790" grpname="CONSCIOUS">conscious</impx>
                        give rise to signal <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affects</impx> (<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx>,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001g.YP0003381516560" grpname="GUILT"
                            >guilt</impx>, shame, etc.). These signal <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx> set defences in motion that reinforce <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx> and quell the unpleasurable signal <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx>. <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defence</impx> &#8216;mechanisms&#8217; include <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>, displacements, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0017025529300" grpname="REACTION FORMATION">reaction
                            formation</impx>, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530"
                            grpname="Projection">projection</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770" grpname="Isolation">isolation</impx>,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950" grpname="Undoing"
                            >undoing</impx> and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0009718260130" grpname="Regression"
                            >regression</impx>. *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >Repression proper</impx> can be considered to be the most effective
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> mechanism insofar as it directly acts to keep the
                        offending <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005442939990"
                            grpname="DRIVE">drive</impx> derivatives or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530" grpname="MEMORY"
                        >memory</impx>-associated <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx> from becoming <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0005451837790" grpname="CONSCIOUS">conscious</impx>.
                        All other <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence mechanisms</impx> exert their effects in a roundabout way.
                            *<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0002322384630"
                            grpname="Displacement">Displacement</impx> acts by finding a substitute
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0007535286680"
                            grpname="SATISFACTION">satisfaction</impx> more acceptable to the ego,
                        thereby diverting <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0019477127470"
                            grpname="ATTENTION">attention</impx> away from the original wishes,
                        fantasies, etc. that are <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YN0015659043440" grpname="BEING">being</impx> kept out
                        of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004696678820"
                            grpname="Consciousness">consciousness</impx>. *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0017025529300" grpname="REACTION FORMATION">Reaction
                            formation</impx> heightens opposite tendencies, for example, overdone
                        expressions of love to hide one\'s hateful feelings. *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530" grpname="Projection"
                            >Projection</impx> externalises the unacceptable wishes, thoughts, etc.,
                        leading the ego to believe these unacceptable psychical contents lie outside
                        of oneself. <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770"
                            grpname="Isolation">Isolation</impx> robs an idea or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530" grpname="MEMORY">memory</impx> of its
                        associated <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affect</impx>, thus rendering the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0016195201530" grpname="MEMORY"
                            >memory</impx> emotionally innocuous, of little psychological
                        consequence. *<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950"
                            grpname="Undoing">Undoing</impx> negates threatening ideas or impulses
                        by performing an act designed to erase them. While <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0002322384630" grpname="Displacement"
                            >displacement</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0017025529300" grpname="REACTION FORMATION">reaction
                            formation</impx>, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530"
                            grpname="Projection">projection</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770" grpname="Isolation">isolation</impx>
                        and <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950" grpname="Undoing"
                            >undoing</impx> are examples of classical types of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence mechanisms</impx>, any <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0016214656090" grpname="EGO FUNCTION">ego
                            function</impx> can be enlisted to function as a <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> mechanism (e.g. <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YP0001969899130" grpname="REALITY TESTING">reality
                            testing</impx>, intellectual activity, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960" grpname="Sublimation"
                            >sublimation</impx>, etc.). *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0009718260130" grpname="Regression"
                            >Regression</impx> also serves as a <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> when it causes the ego to retreat to more primitive
                        levels in order to avoid the wishes and fantasies associated with a later
                        developmental <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0001821354950"
                            grpname="STAGE; PHASE">stage</impx>.</p>
                    <p>R. T.</p>
                </def>
            </dictentry>
            <dictentry>
                <term>DEFENCE (LACAN)</term>
                <src>Skelton, R. (Ed.). (2006). The Edinburgh International Encyclopaedia of
                    Psychoanalysis.</src>
                <def>
                    <p>As early as the late 1940s Lacan strongly questioned the use of the concept
                        of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> made by the *<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0004333631400" grpname="EGO PSYCHOLOGY">ego
                            psychology</impx> school and its supporters. He opposed the debasement
                        of the notion of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> based on its <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0016277282680" grpname="Identification"
                            >identification</impx> with <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0018966170770" grpname="Resistance"
                            >resistance</impx>, presented in terms of what does not give way within
                        the ego in response to the interventions of the analyst. Lacan proposed the
                        notion that if <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0018966170770"
                            grpname="Resistance">resistance</impx> was related to the structural
                        difficulty of saying, then <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> had to be read as <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> against the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005442939990" grpname="DRIVE">drive</impx>. He
                        later refined the notion into that of the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0015186348230" grpname="SUBJECT">subject</impx>\'s
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0013074626040" grpname="RELATION"
                            >relation</impx> to the Real. In taking this step, he was <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YN0015659043440" grpname="BEING"
                            >being</impx> faithful to Freud who, from his first formulations on the
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005442939990" grpname="DRIVE"
                            >drive</impx> in the 1890s, had constructed <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760" grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain"
                            >primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defence</impx> as the initial <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0013074626040" grpname="RELATION">relation</impx>
                        that the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0015186348230"
                            grpname="SUBJECT">subject</impx> establishes with the Real.</p>
                    <p>V. D.</p>
                </def>
            </dictentry>
            <dictentry>
                <term>Defense</term>
                <src>Auchincloss, E. L. and Samberg, E. (2012). Psychoanalytic Terms and
                    Concepts.</src>
                <def>
                    <p><b><impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >Defense</impx></b> is any <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0013420666620" grpname="Unconscious"
                            >unconscious</impx> psychological maneuver used to guard against the
                        experience of a painful inner state. While it is generally agreed that any
                        thought, feeling, or <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YP0012983181060"
                            grpname="BEHAVIOR">behavior</impx> may serve a <b>defensive
                        function</b>, it is possible to describe some specific and commonly used
                                <b><impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defense mechanisms</impx>.</b> Defensive operations begin early in
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0011849316410"
                            grpname="CHILDHOOD">childhood</impx> and continue to operate throughout
                        the life cycle. Some defenses are associated with particular phases of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240" grpname="DEVELOPMENT"
                            >development</impx>. <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defense</impx> is important in both normal mental functioning and in
                        psychopathology. An individual\'s stable <b>defensive style</b> is an
                        important feature of his/ her <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0009492907080" grpname="CHARACTER">character</impx>.
                        Rigid defensive style contributes to <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0009492907080" grpname="CHARACTER">character</impx>
                        pathology, with specific defensive maneuvers associated with specific <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0009492907080" grpname="CHARACTER"
                            >character</impx> types. Defenses also contribute to <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0011868560200"
                            grpname="Symptom; Symptom Formation; Symptomatic Act">symptom</impx>
                        formation, again with specific defenses associated with specific syndromes.
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defense</impx> plays a role in the phenomenon of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0018966170770" grpname="Resistance"
                            >resistance</impx> to analytic treatment. The systematic <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0003576847720" grpname="Interpretation"
                            >interpretation</impx> of this <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0018966170770" grpname="Resistance"
                            >resistance</impx> is termed <b><impx type="TERM2"
                                rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defense</impx> analysis.</b> An aim of contemporary <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0004507089640"
                            grpname="Psycho-Analysis; PSYCHOANALYSIS">psychoanalysis</impx> is to
                        help the patient employ less rigid and more adaptive <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0004974656980" grpname="DEFENSIVE STRATEGIES"
                            >defensive strategies</impx>.</p>
                </def>
                <defrest>
                    <p>The concept of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> is one of the cornerstones of psychoanalytic theory and
                        treatment. While the concept first appeared in the context of Freud\'s new
                        theory of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690"
                            grpname="Hysteria">hysteria</impx>, it quickly became central to his
                        overall <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0011260153880"
                            grpname="Theory of Mind">theory of mind</impx>. <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defense</impx> lies at the center of Freud\'s concept of a <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008220149200" grpname="Dynamic"
                            >dynamic</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0013420666620" grpname="Unconscious"
                            >unconscious</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0007336649800"
                            grpname="CONTAINER; CONTAINED; Containing">containing</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0014567859780"
                            grpname="INSTINCTUAL DRIVE; Instinctual Aim; Instinctual Object"
                            >instinctual drive</impx> derivatives continually pressing for <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0019870290110" grpname="Discharge"
                            >discharge</impx>, countered by opposing forces, or defenses, which
                        serve to prevent their emergence into <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004696678820" grpname="Consciousness"
                            >consciousness</impx>. Although intimately associated with <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0004333631400" grpname="EGO PSYCHOLOGY"
                            >ego psychology</impx> and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                            grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">conflict</impx> theory, the
                        concept of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> is important to most psychoanalytic approaches to the
                        mind and to psychoanalytic treatment.</p>
                    <p>Freud\'s <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B571">(1894c)</bx> first published use of the
                        word <i>defense</i> appeared in 1894 as part of his revolutionary theory of
                                <b><impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defense</impx>
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690" grpname="Hysteria"
                                >hysteria</impx></b> (and all the <b>neuropsychoses of <impx
                                type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defense</impx></b>), as caused not by degenerative mental weakness,
                        but by the ego\'s rejection of an &#8220;incompatible idea.&#8221; In
                        &#8220;Studies on <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690"
                            grpname="Hysteria">Hysteria</impx>,&#8221; Freud (<bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B262">Breuer and Freud, 1893/1895)</bx> elaborated on
                        the role of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> in the formation of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690" grpname="Hysteria">hysteria</impx>,
                        using the word interchangeably with two new words, <i>censorship</i> and
                            <i>repression.</i> After 1897, Freud began to use the word
                            <i>repression</i> almost exclusively when speaking of the ego\'s method
                        of rejecting intolerable or forbidden mental contents from <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004696678820" grpname="Consciousness"
                            >consciousness</impx>. While the term <i>defense</i> appeared from time
                        to time in his work to denote a more inclusive concept than <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>, it was not until 1926, in &#8220;Inhibitions, <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0011868560200"
                            grpname="Symptom; Symptom Formation; Symptomatic Act">Symptoms</impx>
                        and <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY"
                            >Anxiety</impx>,&#8221; that Freud <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B676"
                            >(1926a)</bx> explicitly distinguished between the two, designating
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx> as only one of many kinds of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>. In this same paper, Freud delineated the core of
                        contemporary <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                            grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">conflict</impx> theory,
                        whereby the ego, in response to an <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx>
                        signal, initiates a defensive process that serves to avoid a danger
                        situation associated with an instinctual <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0007446770570" grpname="DEMAND">demand</impx>. When
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> is mobilized, the resulting compromise is in the form of
                        a <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0011868560200"
                            grpname="Symptom; Symptom Formation; Symptomatic Act">symptom</impx>, an
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0016814763690"
                            grpname="INHIBITION">inhibition</impx>, or a wide variety of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0009492907080" grpname="CHARACTER"
                            >character</impx> traits, both pathological and normal. Failure of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> leads to the direct expression of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx>.
                        Even while describing the role of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> in <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0003548993690"
                            grpname="Hysteria">hysteria</impx> and in the mind in general, Freud
                        sought to specify different modes of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> characteristic of different types of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0013496709810" grpname="Neurosis; Neurotic"
                            >neurotic</impx> illnesses. As early as the mid-1890s, in addition to
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>, he described hysterical &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0019761794460" grpname="Conversion"
                            >conversion</impx>,&#8221; obsessional &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0008010190570" grpname="SUBSTITUTION"
                            >substitution</impx>&#8221; and &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0002322384630" grpname="Displacement"
                            >displacement</impx>,&#8221; and paranoid &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530" grpname="Projection"
                            >projection</impx>&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B571">(1894c)</bx>. Later
                        he described &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0017025529300"
                            grpname="REACTION FORMATION">reaction formation</impx>&#8221; and
                            &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960"
                            grpname="Sublimation">sublimation</impx>&#8221; <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B596">(1905b)</bx>, &#8220;isolating&#8221; and
                            &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950"
                            grpname="Undoing">undoing</impx>&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B612"
                            >(1909c)</bx>, &#8220;reversal into its opposite&#8221; and &#8220;<impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YN0005156508250"
                            grpname="Turning Round upon the Subject\'s Own Self">turning round upon
                            the subject\'s own self</impx>&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B641"
                            >(1915b)</bx>, &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015547544960" grpname="Denial; Disavowal"
                            >disavowal</impx>&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B666">(1923b)</bx>,
                            &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0018158705040"
                            grpname="SPLITTING, &#8216;ENFORCED; &#8216;ENFORCED SPLITTING"
                            >splitting</impx>,&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B670">(1924c)</bx>, and
                            &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0003370143270"
                            grpname="Negation">negation</impx>&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B671"
                            >(1925a)</bx>.</p>
                    <p>Various aspects of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> have been central to the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240" grpname="DEVELOPMENT"
                            >development</impx> of post-Freudian psychoanalytic theory. Most
                        notably, A. Freud <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B543">(1936)</bx> made <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> the focus of psychoanalytic <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YN0012766571790" grpname="Technique">technique</impx>
                        and theory by delineating the ego\'s methods of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>, popularizing the term <i>defense mechanism</i> (used
                        occasionally by Freud). She proposed a well-known list of ten specific <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx>: <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0009718260130" grpname="Regression"
                            >regression</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0017025529300" grpname="REACTION FORMATION"
                            >reaction-formation</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770" grpname="Isolation">isolation</impx>,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950" grpname="Undoing"
                            >undoing</impx>, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530"
                            grpname="Projection">projection</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0005203457490" grpname="Introject; Introjection"
                            >introjection</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0001932408610" grpname="TURNING AGAINST THE SELF"
                            >turning against the self</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0008172626820" grpname="Reversal into the Opposite"
                            >reversal into the opposite</impx>, and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960" grpname="Sublimation"
                            >sublimation</impx>. She also described &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015547544960" grpname="Denial; Disavowal"
                            >denial</impx> in <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0010700504210"
                            grpname="Fantasy; Phantasy">fantasy</impx>, word and act,&#8221;
                            &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YP0011373079650"
                            grpname="FIGHT; FLIGHT">flight</impx>,&#8221; &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0003353926610" grpname="IDEALIZATION; Idealisation"
                            >idealization</impx>,&#8221; &#8220;asceticism,&#8221; &#8220;<impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0021236039330"
                            grpname="INTELLECTUALIZATION; Intellectualisation"
                            >intellectualization</impx>,&#8221; &#8220;altruistic surrender,&#8221;
                        &#8220;turning active into passive,&#8221; &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0001932408610" grpname="TURNING AGAINST THE SELF"
                            >turning against the self</impx>,&#8221; and &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0014376592790"
                            grpname="Identification with the Aggressor">identification with the
                            aggressor</impx>&#8221; as methods of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>. A. Freud argued that <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> are always comingled, functioning as part of
                        a broader array of <b>defensive measures</b>; she also observed that any
                        mental activity (<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0010700504210"
                            grpname="Fantasy; Phantasy">fantasy</impx>, thought, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YP0012983181060" grpname="BEHAVIOR">behavior</impx>,
                        and others) can be used for defensive purposes. In addition, A. Freud showed
                        how <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> can be directed not only against instinctual aims, but
                        also against any mental activity that might give rise to unpleasurable <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affect</impx>, including thoughts, memories,
                        actions, and <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affects</impx> themselves. Finally, she
                        studied the chronological <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240" grpname="DEVELOPMENT"
                            >development</impx> of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> and attempted to correlate specific defenses with types
                        of psychopathology.</p>
                    <p>Following the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0013300865870"
                            grpname="DEATH">death</impx> of Freud, W. Reich explored how an
                        individual\'s defensive operations are expressed in his &#8220;<impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0009492907080" grpname="CHARACTER"
                            >character</impx> armor&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1429">(W. Reich,
                            1933/1945)</bx>. In the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240" grpname="DEVELOPMENT"
                            >development</impx> of her <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0010361003460"
                            grpname="OBJECT RELATION; OBJECT RELATIONS">object relations</impx>
                        theory, Klein <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1024">(1946)</bx> described <b>primitive
                            defenses</b>, which, in her view, arise as early as the first year of
                        life (directed against <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430"
                            grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx> derived from the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0013300865870" grpname="DEATH">death</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0006585309640"
                            grpname="Instinct; Instinctualization">instinct</impx>) and play a role
                        in the formation of the inner world. The most prominent of these defenses
                        are &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0018158705040"
                            grpname="SPLITTING, &#8216;ENFORCED; &#8216;ENFORCED SPLITTING"
                            >splitting</impx>,&#8221; &#8220;primitive <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0003353926610" grpname="IDEALIZATION; Idealisation"
                            >idealization</impx>,&#8221; and &#8220;<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0014993008580" grpname="Projective Identification"
                            >projective identification</impx>.&#8221; These defenses are prominent
                        during the paranoid (paranoid-<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0001483907170" grpname="Schizoid">schizoid</impx>)
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000489824390" grpname="Position"
                            >position</impx>. Defenses against <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001g.YP0003381516560" grpname="GUILT">guilt</impx> and
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0016359868500"
                            grpname="DEPRESSION">depression</impx> during the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0014973543540" grpname="Depressive Position"
                            >depressive position</impx> include turning away from the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070" grpname="Object"
                            >object</impx>, reversion to the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0014973543540" grpname="Depressive Position"
                            >depressive position</impx>, <b>manic defenses</b>, and, ultimately,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YP0007319693790"
                            grpname="Reparation">reparation</impx> (Klein <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1020">1935</bx>, <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1022"
                        >1940</bx>). In the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240"
                            grpname="DEVELOPMENT">development</impx> of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0004708039940" grpname="SELF PSYCHOLOGY">self
                            psychology</impx>, Kohut (<bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1044">1971</bx>, <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1047">1977</bx>) distinguished between <b><impx
                                type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005895097250"
                                grpname="DEFENSIVE STRUCTURES">defensive structures</impx></b>,
                        which serve to cover over a <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0000702800760" grpname="Primary; Secondary Gain"
                            >primary</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0001256809230" grpname="Defect"
                            >defect</impx> in <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0002234623310"
                            grpname="The Self">the self</impx>, and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0013728776860"
                            grpname="Compensatory Structure; COMPENSATORY STRUCTURES">compensatory
                            structures</impx>, which seek to compensate for that <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0001256809230" grpname="Defect">defect</impx>. He
                        also proposed the concept of the defensive <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001v.YP0019850641680" grpname="VERTICAL SPLIT">vertical
                            split</impx>, which serves to protect against the experience of shame
                        and humiliation of unmet narcissistic needs, while simultaneously enacting
                        these needs. Both Klein and Kohut expanded the list of kinds of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY"
                            >anxiety</impx>, or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affect</impx>, that have the power to trigger <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>.</p>
                    <p>In the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240"
                            grpname="DEVELOPMENT">development</impx> of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0007210729000"
                            grpname="INTERPERSONAL PSYCHOANALYSIS">interpersonal
                            psychoanalysis</impx>, Sullivan <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1683">(1953a)</bx>
                        coined the term &#8220;safety operations&#8221; (the basis for which is
                            &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0008026754820"
                            grpname="SELECTIVE INATTENTION">selective inattention</impx>&#8221;),
                        which are roughly analogous to defenses. However, Sullivan argued that what
                        is defended against are not intrapsychic events, but aspects of
                        relationships with others that, for a variety of reasons, cannot be attended
                        to and are therefore unformulated, or dissociated. Elaborating on these
                        ideas, D. B. Stern argued that <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0014507665690" grpname="DISSOCIATION"
                            >dissociation</impx>, defined as the defensive and motivated
                        preservation of experience in an unformulated state, is the most important
                        form of motivated not-knowing confronting the psychoanalytic clinician <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1634">(D. B. Stern, 1997)</bx>. Modell <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1259">(1984)</bx> extended the definition of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> mechanism to the &#8220;two-person&#8221; (rather than
                        solely intrapsychic) context. Interpersonal and relational psychoanalysts
                        have continued to develop this concept of <b>interpersonal <impx
                                type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                                grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                                >defense</impx></b>
                        <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1779">(Westerman and Steen, 2009)</bx>. For example,
                        mystification is an interpersonal <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> aimed at interfering with another\'s capacity to think
                        about or understand some aspect of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0014605906430" grpname="REALITY">reality</impx> by
                        substituting a false <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YP0008360089310"
                            grpname="Reconstruction; Construction">construction</impx> of that <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0014605906430" grpname="REALITY"
                            >reality</impx> (<bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1085">Laing, 1965</bx>; <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1114">Levenson, 1972</bx>).</p>
                    <p>Other points of view include those of D. N. Stern, who argued that methods of
                        negotiating repair in the inevitable missteps within the intersubjective
                        field during <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240"
                            grpname="DEVELOPMENT">development</impx> form the foundation for <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>
                        <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1641">(D. N. Stern, 2005)</bx>. Looking at <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> from the point of view of meaning rather than mechanism,
                        Schafer <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1508">(1968a)</bx> stressed the <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YN0000880314790" grpname="Narrative"
                            >narrative</impx> content embedded in all defensive operations. C.
                        Brenner <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B252">(1982)</bx> questioned the utility of the
                        concept of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> altogether, as a distinct class of ego functions,
                        arguing that all defenses can be recruited for nondefensive purposes, and
                        that all kinds of mental activity and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YP0012983181060" grpname="BEHAVIOR">behavior</impx>
                        can be recruited for <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>. In contrast to Brenner, Gray <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B789"
                            >(1994)</bx> has proposed a theory of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YN0012766571790" grpname="Technique">technique</impx>
                        called &#8220;<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0014849623780"
                            grpname="Close Process Attention">close process attention</impx>,&#8221;
                        based almost entirely on the analysis of defenses, which he believes can be
                        identified.</p>
                    <p>Many psychoanalytic theorists have attempted to classify and organize the
                        defenses systematically. Fenichel <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B483">(1945)</bx>
                        attempted to distinguish between <b>successful defenses</b> and
                            <b>unsuccessful defenses.</b> G. Bibring et al. <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B162">(1961)</bx> classified the defenses along a
                        gradient of complexity, ranging from &#8220;first-order&#8221; or
                        irreducible mechanisms to &#8220;second-order&#8221; defensive behavioral
                        patterns that involve combinations of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx>. Using empirical data gathered from a
                        longitudinal study of men, Vaillant <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1732">(1992a)</bx>
                        organized <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> into <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001g.YN0000582685180" grpname="GROUP; GROUPS">groups</impx>
                        related to their adaptive function and developmental level: psychotic (<impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015547544960"
                            grpname="Denial; Disavowal">denial</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530" grpname="Projection"
                            >projection</impx>), immature (<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0010700504210" grpname="Fantasy; Phantasy"
                            >fantasy</impx>, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530"
                            grpname="Projection">projection</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0006654185660" grpname="ACTING OUT; Acting In"
                            >acting out</impx>), <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0013496709810" grpname="Neurosis; Neurotic"
                            >neurotic</impx> (<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0021236039330"
                            grpname="INTELLECTUALIZATION; Intellectualisation"
                            >intellectualization</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0002322384630" grpname="Displacement"
                            >displacement</impx>, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>), and mature defenses (humor, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0016102569410" grpname="Altruism">altruism</impx>,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960"
                            grpname="Sublimation">sublimation</impx>). From a point of view
                        integrating ego-psychological and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0010361003460"
                            grpname="OBJECT RELATION; OBJECT RELATIONS">object relations</impx>
                        perspectives, Kernberg <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B973">(1970a)</bx> developed a
                        hierarchical theory of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0021254895470"
                            grpname="PERSONALITY; Personality Disorder">personality</impx>
                        organization (psychotic, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YN0013905962660" grpname="Borderline"
                            >borderline</impx>, and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001n.YP0013496709810" grpname="Neurosis; Neurotic"
                            >neurotic</impx>) based on the differential utilization of defenses,
                        organized along an axis of less mature, or primitive, to more mature.
                        However, Willick <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1785">(1983)</bx> and others warned
                        of the pitfalls of any system of classification, especially those that refer
                        to primitive defenses, arguing that everyone uses all defenses in various
                        contexts. Undaunted, Blackman <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B179">(2004)</bx>
                        expanded the catalog of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> to a record high of 101.</p>
                    <p>Defensive operations have been the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070" grpname="Object">object</impx> of
                        much empirical investigation, both within <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0004507089640"
                            grpname="Psycho-Analysis; PSYCHOANALYSIS">psychoanalysis</impx> and in
                        cognitive and social psychology, where the concept of &#8220;coping
                        mechanism&#8221; overlaps with <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>. For example, much effort has been made to develop
                        instruments to objectively measure the use of specific defenses for research
                        purposes <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1358">(Perry and Lanni, 2008)</bx>. Many
                        other investigators have studied how defenses operate in a variety of
                        contexts <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1776">(Westen, 1999b)</bx>. For example,
                        empirical studies show that <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> may retain broad cross-cultural applicability <bx
                            r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1707">(Tori and Bilmes, 2002)</bx>, may differ between
                        men and women <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B284">(Bullitt and Farber, 2002)</bx>,
                        and may change with successful treatment <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1467">(Roy et
                            al., 2009)</bx>. Cramer <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B364">(2006)</bx> has
                        reviewed empirical <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001k.YP0010110936630"
                            grpname="KNOWLEDGE">knowledge</impx> about how defenses develop,
                        function, and change, as well as research methods for their assessment.
                        Finally, cognitive neuroscientists have turned their <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0019477127470" grpname="ATTENTION">attention</impx>
                        to understanding the biological underpinnings of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>
                        <bx r="ZBK.161.0291A.B1289">(Northoff and Boeker, 2006)</bx>.</p>
                </defrest>
