                <term>DEFENSE</term>
            </dictentry>
            <dictentry>
                <term>DEFENSE</term>
                <term>Defense Mechanism</term>
                <src>Moore, B. and Fine, B. (1990). Psychoanalytic Terms and Concepts</src>
                <dictalso>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0018611654130"
                        grpname="COMPROMISE FORMATION">COMPROMISE FORMATION</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004220765300"
                        grpname="CONFLICT; INTRAPSYCHIC CONFLICT">CONFLICT</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015547544960"
                        grpname="Denial; Disavowal">DENIAL</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0006965204600" grpname="Ego">EGO</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001e.YN0016214656090" grpname="EGO FUNCTION">EGO
                        FUNCTION</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0011758250570"
                        grpname="Internalisation; INTERNALIZATION">INTERNALIZATION</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YN0000469822530" grpname="Projection"
                        >PROJECTION</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0009718260130" grpname="Regression"
                        >REGRESSION</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                        grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                        >REPRESSION</impx>
                    <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960" grpname="Sublimation"
                        >SUBLIMATION</impx>
                </dictalso>
                <defrest>
                    <p><i>Defense</i> is a general term describing the ego\'s active struggle to
                        protect against dangers&#8212;typically, loss of the love <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070" grpname="Object">object</impx>, loss
                        of the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070"
                            grpname="Object">object</impx>\'s love, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0001835728720"
                            grpname="CASTRATION; Castration Complex">castration</impx>, and <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YN0003128406840"
                            grpname="SUPEREGO; Super-Ego">superego</impx> disapproval&#8212;and
                        their attendant unpleasant <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060" grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS"
                            >affects</impx> during <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0008047204240" grpname="DEVELOPMENT"
                            >development</impx> and throughout life. A repressed wish, idea, or
                        feeling that has become associated with some real or fantasied punishment
                        threatens to erupt into <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004696678820" grpname="Consciousness"
                            >consciousness</impx>. Painful feelings of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0015404992430" grpname="ANXIETY">anxiety</impx>,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0016359868500"
                            grpname="DEPRESSION">depression</impx>, shame, or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001g.YP0003381516560" grpname="GUILT">guilt</impx> ensue as
                        signal <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affects</impx>, impelling the ego to ward off
                        the wish or <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005442939990"
                            grpname="DRIVE">drive</impx>. <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defense</impx> operates unconsciously; the individual does not
                        recognize the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> he or she uses to ward off dangerous drives
                        or wishes. The operation of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> may delete or distort aspects of <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0014605906430" grpname="REALITY"
                            >reality</impx>.</p>
                    <p>The term <i>defense</i> was first used by Freud in &#8220;The Neuro-Psychoses
                        of <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defense</impx>&#8221; <bx r="ZBK.064.0048A.B008">(18 94)</bx>, but for
                        many years he used <i>repression</i> and <i>defense</i> interchangeably. The
                        term <i>defense mechanism</i> appeared for the first time in <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001f.YN0016730370470"
                            grpname="Freud, Anna; Anna Freud">Anna Freud</impx>\'s classic <i>The
                            Ego and the Mechanisms of Defense</i>
                        <bx r="ZBK.064.0048A.B004">(1936)</bx>, which described ten activities or
                        methods of ego functioning in the service of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>.</p>
                    <p><impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >Defense mechanisms</impx> operate singly or occur together in
                        everchanging and interrelating patterns, utilizing various behaviors, ideas,
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affects</impx>, aspects of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0009492907080" grpname="CHARACTER">character</impx>,
                        other ego functions, and even drives. For this reason the usefulness of the
                        concept of specific <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> has been questioned. Any aspect of ego
                        functioning may be used in the service of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx>, and a <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> is so <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0011849881830" grpname="Complex">complex</impx> that
                        delineating single mechanisms can be reductionistic and misleading <bx
                            r="ZBK.064.0048A.B002">(Brenner, 1981)</bx>. Nevertheless, many analysts
                        find it useful to employ <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> to describe the effect of the defenses in
                        regard to the dangers to the ego. Brief descriptions of some principal <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> follow:</p>
                    <p><i>Repression</i>. Withholds, expels, or forgets an idea or feeling. It may
                        exclude from awareness what was once experienced consciously or may stop
                        ideas and feelings from reaching <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004696678820" grpname="Consciousness"
                            >consciousness</impx> at all. A person may, for example, be unaware of
                        feelings of hatred directed at a parent or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0005555951430" grpname="SIBLING">sibling</impx>.
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >Repression</impx> operates throughout life, regularly occurring in
                        respect to <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0011849316410"
                            grpname="CHILDHOOD">childhood</impx> events during the crucial period
                        before six years of age (<impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0009241119700"
                            grpname="AMNESIA, INFANTILE; INFANTILE AMNESIA">infantile
                        amnesia</impx>).</p>
                    <p><i>Displacement</i>. Shifts the focus or emphasis in <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0010931565630" grpname="DREAMS; DREAMING"
                            >dreams</impx> and <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001b.YP0012983181060"
                            grpname="BEHAVIOR">behavior</impx>, generally by diverting the interest
                        or intensity (<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0005377732370"
                            grpname="Cathexis">cathexis</impx>) attached to one idea onto another
                        idea that is associatively related but more acceptable to the ego. Thus
                        exhibitionistic wishes may be displaced from the genitals to the body as a
                        whole. In a <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0010931565630"
                            grpname="DREAMS; DREAMING">dream</impx> the most important elements of
                        the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001l.YP0011280027370"
                            grpname="Latent Content">latent content</impx> may be represented by
                        apparently insignificant details.</p>
                    <p><i>Reaction formation</i>. Changes the unacceptable to acceptable, thereby
                        also ensuring the efficient maintenance of <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0007443847010"
                            grpname="Repression; Repression Barrier; Repression Proper; REPRESSION, PRIMAL; PRIMAL REPRESSION"
                            >repression</impx>. A painful idea or feeling is replaced in <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0005451837790" grpname="CONSCIOUS"
                            >conscious</impx> awareness by its opposite. For example, a <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0007842646530" grpname="Child"
                            >child</impx> who has repressed feelings of hate toward <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YN0010769193550" grpname="MOTHER"
                            >mother</impx> may develop an extreme solicitousness and <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0013670796210" grpname="CONCERN"
                            >concern</impx> for her welfare.</p>
                    <p><i>Projection</i>. Externalizes the objectionable <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0003470182460" grpname="IMPULSE">impulse</impx> or
                        idea by attributing it to another person or to some perhaps mystical force
                        in the outside world. (&#8220;The devil did it.&#8221;) The intolerable idea
                        or wish may be transformed before it is projected&#8212;Freud inferred, for
                        example, that paranoid ideas are based on <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0013420666620" grpname="Unconscious"
                            >unconscious</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001h.YP0021374133010"
                            grpname="Homosexuality; Lesbianism">homosexuality</impx>. First the
                        feeling of homosexual love is transformed into hatred, then the hatred is
                        projected onto the person who was the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001o.YN0004676559070" grpname="Object">object</impx> of the
                        unacceptable love. That person is then seen as a persecutor.</p>
                    <p><i>Isolation</i>. Separates a painful idea or event from feelings associated
                        with it, thereby altering its emotional impact. There are several types of
                            <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770"
                            grpname="Isolation">isolation</impx>. Two or more related thoughts or
                        feelings may be separated: for instance, the idea, &#8220;I am angry at
                        her&#8221; and another thought, &#8220;She left me,&#8221; are separated by
                        time, and the causal connection is thereby lost. Or ideas may appear simply
                        without the <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0005451837790"
                            grpname="CONSCIOUS">conscious</impx>
                        <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001p.YP0016733341930" grpname="PRESENCE"
                            >presence</impx> of associated feelings. Fleeting aggressive
                        thoughts&#8212;plunging a knife into someone, throwing a <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YP0007842646530" grpname="Child">child</impx> out of a
                        window, shouting obscenities in a public place&#8212;often occur without the
                        emotion (anger) appropriate to such thoughts. Such <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770" grpname="Isolation">isolation</impx>
                        deprives the thought of motivational force and hence of intent; the thought
                        seems alien, <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0005417015680"
                            grpname="ACTION">action</impx> is thwarted, and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001g.YP0003381516560" grpname="GUILT">guilt</impx> is
                        sometimes avoided.</p>
                    <p><i>Undoing</i>. Ritualistically &#8220;removes&#8221; the offensive act,
                        sometimes by atoning for it. Particularly in compulsive neuroses, a
                            two-<impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0001821354950"
                            grpname="STAGE; PHASE">stage</impx> act may symbolize expression of an
                        aggressive or sexual wish and its reversal or <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001u.YP0015001128950" grpname="Undoing">undoing</impx>.
                        Some individuals habitually commit transgressions and try to undo them by
                        religious or self-punitive expiations.</p>
                    <p>Many other <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense mechanisms</impx> have been described. While the function of
                        all these mechanisms is the same&#8212;to protect against painful <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YP0005740675060"
                            grpname="AFFECT; AFFECTS">affects</impx>&#8212;they achieve this aim in
                        different ways. <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001r.YN0009718260130"
                            grpname="Regression">Regression</impx> works by effecting a retreat to
                        an earlier <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0001821354950"
                            grpname="STAGE; PHASE">phase</impx> of psychic organization; <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0005203457490"
                            grpname="Introject; Introjection">introjection</impx> and <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YP0016277282680" grpname="Identification"
                            >identification</impx>, by taking inside <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0002234623310" grpname="The Self">the self</impx>
                        what is threatening; <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YN0015547544960"
                            grpname="Denial; Disavowal">denial</impx>, by pretending a threatening
                        situation is not there; <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001s.YP0020102002960" grpname="Sublimation"
                            >sublimation</impx>, by changing the form of the unacceptable <impx
                            type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0005442939990" grpname="DRIVE"
                            >drive</impx> to one that is acceptable; and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0001932408610" grpname="TURNING AGAINST THE SELF"
                            >turning against the self</impx>, by redirecting the <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0003470182460" grpname="IMPULSE">impulse</impx> from
                        outside to inside, from another person to <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0002234623310" grpname="The Self">the self</impx>.
                        (This <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0011147975280"
                            grpname="DEFENSE; Defence; Defense Mechanism; Defence Mechanisms"
                            >defense</impx> is operative especially in <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001d.YP0016359868500" grpname="DEPRESSION"
                            >depression</impx> and <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001m.YP0014741157210" grpname="Masochism"
                        >masochism</impx>.)</p>
                    <p>Defenses may also function constructively making <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001a.YN0005417015680" grpname="ACTION">action</impx> and
                        thought more efficient. These might be called <i>adaptive mechanisms</i> or
                            <i>autonomous ego functions</i>. For instance, <impx type="TERM2"
                            rx="ZBK.069.0001i.YN0001477504770" grpname="Isolation">isolation</impx>,
                        by dissociating <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001t.YP0007326625520"
                            grpname="Thinking">thinking</impx> from emotions, can facilitate the
                        logical progression of ideas by avoiding the distraction associated emotions
                        might <impx type="TERM2" rx="ZBK.069.0001c.YN0004867612400" grpname="CAUSE"
                            >cause</impx>.</p>
                </defrest>
